title: Finally! A good cell phone car product.
text: I have the WORST luck with things like this, so I was getting ready to return this before it even got here, but I'm happy to report that it works well! I have a large, heavy, TCL phone, so I was fully prepared for the phone to be too heavy for the holder, but the heavy-duty, adjustable neck is able to hold it just fine, even while I'm driving. I actually have to put some strength into adjusting the neck - that's how heavy-duty it is. You can also adjust the base so that it fills up your cup holder, providing a nice solid foundation. I was bummed when I got a new car recently and learned that my model didn't have the GPS appear on the car's screen, so I was concerned that if I needed to use GPS I would still need to do so unsafely. But (and this may be my only gripe with this product) this holder essentially keeps your phone up to your nose so you can see it easily without taking your eyes off the road for too long. Suggestion: it's probably better to use this in your back cupholder because if it's in the front one, you may bang into it when going into gear. This won't dislodge it or anything, but it could distract you while you're driving, which could be dangerous.

title: Good phone, flimsy materials
text:
I originally had an LG Tribute with 4 GB of memory, and I unfortunately needed to replace it after less than two years because of normal updates taking up most of my memory. This phone makes a viable substitute, as it has more memory, so I can use apps again (I deleted everything off of my old phone and still did not have room). Plus, and most importantly, it has all of the same programs that I use regularly (Chrome, Maps, Bluetooth capability, etc.). I was able to keep my phone number, since I am just transferring phones and not providers ("still [using Virgin Mobile] after all these years"), and it was super easy to add this phone to my account. It prompts you right in the phone to substitute this phone with your old phone, so you basically do everything through a pre-programmed app - easy peasy. Normally, I am not a fan of the bigger displays, because I am big on carrying my phones in my pocket, but I actually thoroughly enjoy the bigger display on this phone because I can read more text messages at once, and videos are significantly larger. Plus, I find I am "enlarging" things a lot less because the font is bigger. Websites that are built to be mobile-friendly are more easy to view on the crystal-clear display.

The only issue I have so far with this phone is that it could not be made out of flimsier material. I dropped it outside my car today after not even owning it for 24 hours, and it already has no less than four scratches along the border. Also, there is a tiny piece of plastic running along the top of the phone and covering the power button on the back - be sure to remove those (I didn't realize they were there until this morning). And yes, the power button/volume buttons are those flat buttons on the back. I consulted the user's manual, and I *still* couldn't figure out where they were. Just found them by trial and error.

Oh, one more thing: the stylus is great - it seems like it's made out of a kind of material that makes it look like a tiny microphone. Though, once you pop it out, there's a little pen symbol that appears in the top right of the phone, should you want to use any of the stylus-related apps. If you visit a web page with a "search" magnifying glass in this same corner, you will have to put the stylus back and use your finger in order to search, since the pen symbol appears right over the magnifying glass.

All in, I am thoroughly enjoying this phone and am happy with my purchase. Just be sure to purchase a case to go with it, since it WILL get scratched immediately after dropping it. You don't get any second chances with these materials.

title: Perfect for my needs.
text: The perfect phone for me.  This is my first smartphone, and I don't really need it to do much.  All I need is the capability of checking my e-mail via a quick and reliable connection while on the road, and this delivers.  I was also able to upgrade my phone easily through the Virgin Mobile site, so there was no worry about needing to change my phone number (I got to keep my old one).  Swiping makes sending text messages much easier and faster, and multiple messages are combined to read as one long message - infinitely more effective than having to wait for each message to send separately like with my old phone.  Plus, I can now use the Bluetooth feature in my car, which is an infinitely safer way to take a call.  I only pay $38 a month for my pay-as-you-go contract with Virgin Mobile, and I love it.  I refuse to pay upwards of $65 a month for the same service elsewhere.  With an SD card (because it doesn't come with a lot of memory), you can store music and photos on this phone, just like any other, and you can download apps like Amazon Music (to stream your music library or listen to Prime music for free), or apps that connect you to your personal bank and e-mail.  I had originally installed the Facebook app but uninstalled it after receiving constant notifications on my phone every time there was an update.  Just as effective is to keep Facebook open in a Chrome window on the phone and access it whenever you need to - it updates in real time so it's essentially the same thing as the app, without the annoying pop-ups.  I like my phone to alert me when something important is happening, not just because a friend of a friend commented on a friend's status.  The only thing I don't like is that if you miss a call or a text message, the only way to know is to remember to check your phone - this is particularly a pain if you use your phone for business.  I have only ever owned one phone in my lifetime that featured a blinking light until you tended to the missed notification.  I have been trying to find an app that will allow me to do this, but the only ones I have found thus far are those that control the LED light of the (fantastic) camera on the phone, but that light (flash) is crazy bright and not really helpful if the phone is laying down or in your pocket, the only two places where a phone would normally be.  And if you're holding the phone already, the LED light going off won't be very helpful, since you're probably already aware of an incoming call/text message.  Photos come out perfect when you have good lighting, though this phone's camera isn't the best at compensating for dull lighting.  You can flip it to be front-facing or rear-facing, so you can use it for selfies or like a regular camera.  The video quality is impeccable, though, as it holds a pretty good steady cam despite my shaky hands.  All in, this phone was perfect for the "I pretty much stole it" price, and you just can't compete with the $38 a month that Virgin Mobile charges.  Even their most expensive plan is still cheaper than the run-of-the-mill plan that other phones come with, and I don't need all that their most expensive plan has to offer.  This plan with this phone perfectly meets my needs.

2. The stylus end is a soft fabric covered cushion, shaped like a pencil eraser. After one month of constant use with the same stylus on my tablet (can you say "games"), the fabric stylus end squished flatter than it did originally when it was pressed down on a screen. It popped up back into shape when it wasn't being pressed down, it didn't stop working and it didn't start scratching. But the squishiness made it harder to be exact. For most of the games I play, the flattened surface is not a problem and I continue to use the old stylus. But checking links on websites, or changing pages on an amazon list just need more care (or expanding the view) when using a stylus where the end squashes flatter. As these are inexpensive styluses, this may or may not be a problem. So far it hasn't been a game changer for me.

title: A lot of work to replace, but it does help a little bit with better signal.
text:
Seems to have helped fix my wifes Iphone 6 with her not being able to find broadcasting wifi signals. Its not a task for the light of heart. It is a real pain to get this this antenna in the phone. It is behind the logic board, so you have to take everything out first. Overall took about a 1.5 hours to take apart and put back together, and phone seems to getting better signal.
Don't be misled about other parts to fix the wifi. The wifi chip is soldered into the logic board. It is not removeable. The other item people seem to but is a cover for the wifi chip, and then they wonder why it still doesn't work. Make sure you get the right parts if you are going to take on this endeavor. You will encounter impossibly small screws, and you will need a eyeglass repair flathead screw driver which does NOT come with this set, which is why I dinged it one star. There is only one screw (the standoff screw) which requires a tiny flathead, and without it, you aren't getting the logic board out to replace this antenna.

title: Good, Needs Improvement
text:
We wanted a fairly simple phone for our 11-year-old daughter which had some good parental controls on it. This one seemed to be the best mix of simplicity and still allowing her the futures she wants such as texting, camera, music, and limited Internet access. It also allows me to track her with GPS tracking so that I know where she is at any given time.

We had it for two months now. And I can see there are some things I really like about it, and some things I really don't.

PROS:
GPS tracking for parent (mostly accurate)
Child can text
Child can make phone calls with no limit on contacts ( unless restricted by parent )
Child can access the Internet with some effort, meaning she's not on there much ( websites can be restricted by parent )
Has a camera (decent, not great)
Has an MP3 player
Limited memory ( keeps my daughter from downloading too many apps/games, which I consider a pro )
Uses Google App Store
Added phone to my AT&T plan (new SIM card)
WiFi enabled

CONS:
GPS tracking is not always accurate. Sometimes it tells me she is somewhere she is not, sometimes it alerts me she has left the safe zone when she is sitting right next to me, but probably 90% accurate
Because this is an off â€“ market brand, you cannot buy accessories for it
Instructions/set up guide are very basic. I've had to write to the creator multiple times to ask how to do simple things, and because this is an off â€“ market brand, you can't google it
Although there are parental controls for things like contacts and websites, it appears you can only turn on all of them or none of them and not restrict particular ones, but I'm not sure about this as I haven't had to restrict anything yet.
Lost of features you'd expect if you are used to smart phones are not available on this phone. For example, you cannot send JPEG files in a text. My daughter and I like sending pics and you can't do this. The phone also did not come with Emoji's, which every child wants. I had to download a separate Emoji app and then contact the creator of the phone for it to start working.
After 2 months the screen is cracked in 2 places. Because this is an off brand, you cannot get a screen protector or a case for it, so it is inevitable that it will get dropped and broken.

Overall, I think this is a decent phone for an 11-year-old. I didn't want her to have a smart phone with full access to all apps and Internet use. So for that I like it. She loves it. It's mostly me that is picky about it.

I think the GPS tracking is decent for my child's needs. However, the cracks are a problem and I do not see this phone lasting a super long time. I think it needs a little more work to bring it up to snuff. And it would help tremendously if a case and screen protector were available.

So I've now purchased 5 different brands of screen protectors advertised for the 45mm. This is the first that covers the entire screen. However the aggravation of installing and cheap feel doesn't make up for it.

If you've ever done a wet install then this shouldn't be different. But it is. It's needlessly aggravating.

Removing these protectors from their backing is maddening. Being sure to wet fingers, necessary to prevent your fingerprints under it, but makes what is already difficult even more so. You have to be very, very careful to not stretch or pinch it.

Once off actually installing is easy, but forget a perfect install. Bubbles, bubbles and more bubbles. The solution provided is horrible. Letting it sit only ensures the bubbles and imperfections are permanent. I can tell easily that this will peel up as soon as it â€œdriesâ€.

The feel is plastic fantastic. The same as any film you'd use but with a slight rubbery undertone, if you will. Honestly not looking for glass feel but this feels cheap. Like $1 cheap. The responsiveness is good, no issues with touch or swiping. Speaking of swiping, edge swipes will catch on the protector and you'll be further reminded there is a piece of plastic there.

Where there isn't a squiggly wrinkle looking thing or bubbles that persist the clarity is ok. You know it's there, no way around it. It adds a glossy kinda meh to the screen that won't get better with time.

I guess you need to ask yourself if complete coverage is worth the aggravating ugly result to get it. Not sure why the Series 7 45mm is so hard to make a full coverage quality protector for. I would suggest you do what I'm going to doâ€¦keep looking.
